audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:1:# E4 empirical anchors — from the established F↔G literature (harvested 2026-07-11)
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:3:> The standalone "foundational F-vs-G" paper was dropped (its result is already established — see
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:4:> `individual-vs-estimated-value/docs/prior-art-review.md`). The **win**: that literature gives E4's central-arm
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:5:> estimation model a **measured, citable** anchor instead of assumed parameters. Below: what each source pins,
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:6:> and how it maps to E4's parameter registry. **Caveat:** most of this is political-OPINION perception, not
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:7:> public-project VALUE — a transport argument is required; magnitudes may not carry over, but the **mechanism,
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:8:> the structural form, and plausible ranges** do.
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:10:## 1. Structural form of the central's estimate — LINEAR WITH INTERCEPT SHIFT
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:11:**Broockman & Skovron (2018, APSR)**, 3,765 US state politicians, 9 issues: politicians' perceptions of
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:12:constituent opinion show *"a strong and strikingly linear relationship"* with reality **plus a substantial
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:13:"intercept shift"** — they track reality (responsive slope) but with a **systematic directional bias**.
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:14:→ **E4 mapping:** model the central's estimate as `Ĝ = a + b·(true) + noise` — a *responsive* slope `b` and a
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:15:**systematic bias intercept `a`**, not random error. This is the honest, data-backed form for the central arm
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:16:(replaces the ad-hoc ρ_proxy/τ story the round-8 critique rejected).
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:18:## 2. Magnitude of the planner bias — anchored ranges
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:19:- **Broockman & Skovron (2018):** overestimation of conservative support by **~7 to ~36 percentage points**
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:20:  (issue-dependent; often >10, sometimes >20) on a 0–100 support scale. Welfare example: actual ≈9%, perceived
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:21:  ≈32% (~23-pt gap).
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:22:- **Dias, Lucas & Sheffer ("Beyond the mean", PSRM 2026):** 1,865 Canadian municipal politicians + 94k citizens;
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:23:  point-estimate perceptual error **≈0.53–0.71** on the ideological scale; **~30%** place residents on the wrong
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:24:  side of the midpoint. Comparable to the male–female ideological gap (~0.5).
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:25:→ **E4 mapping:** the intercept-shift bias `a` is **materially non-zero and large** in real elite estimation —
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:26:  a defensible *range*, not a hand-wave. (Transport to project-value context is an explicit assumption.)
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:28:## 3. The bias is partly a MEASUREMENT/format artifact — and distributions matter
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:29:- **Dias–Lucas–Sheffer:** a **"perceived-distribution" task cuts the bias roughly IN HALF.** Politicians think of
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:30:  constituencies as **diverse groups with different preferences, not an "average" constituent**, and elicit more
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:31:  accurately when drawing distributions.
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:32:- **Dias et al. (2025):** point estimates **exaggerate** perceived polarization; drawing the distribution yields
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:33:  far more modest, accurate perceptions.
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:34:→ **E4 mapping:** (a) model value as a **distribution F, not a point** — vindicated by how planners actually
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:35:  reason; (b) the perceived-vs-actual **dispersion σ** is itself mis-estimated, and *how you elicit it* changes
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:36:  the bias by ~2×. Two honest consequences: the central's error has a reducible (format) component and an
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:37:  irreducible (projection/information) component.
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:39:## 4. The projection weight `w` is real, LARGE, and DIRECTIONAL — sweep it (anti "forced ugliness")
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:40:- **Gagnon-Bartsch et al. (interpersonal projection experiment):** a formal model where the prediction of others
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:41:  W(m, s_j | s_i, i) loads on **own state `s_i`** iff the projection parameter α>0 (and is constant in `s_i` when
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:42:  α=0). Reduced-form magnitudes are **large and directional**: "fresh" predictors **over-estimated** tired
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:43:  workers' willingness-to-work by **~50%**; "tired" predictors **under-estimated** fresh workers' by **~21%**
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:44:  (the cleaner measure); a within-subject flip (Group I) lowered guesses by ~19% (4.22 tasks, p<.001).
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:45:  Interpersonal projection (~50%) **exceeds** the intrapersonal analog (~30%). They decompose the error into
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:46:  **projection ≈ task-uncertainty** (roughly equal halves). *(Correction: the `α=0.01` in the paper is the cost
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:47:  curvature, not the projection weight — projection here is substantial, not near-zero.)*
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:48:- **Dias–Lucas–Sheffer:** projection is directional — politicians **start from constituents near their own
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:49:  position** ("self-similar constituents more accessible"), reinforcing conservative bias for right-leaning,
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:50:  counterbalancing for left-leaning. So `w > 0`, **signed by the planner's own position vs the population mean**.
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:51:→ **E4 mapping:** projection is **materially non-zero, directional, and context-varying in magnitude** (≈20–50%
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:52:  in these tasks). E4 should **sweep `w` over a plausible, sizable range** and report the surface — the honesty is
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:53:  in the *range and direction*, not in pretending the central is either perfect or horrific. Where good proxies +
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:54:  small `w` → central ties/wins; where projection + biased information bite → the distributed arm wins; **the
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:55:  boundary is the object.**
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:57:## 5. Parameter-registry status after this harvest
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:58:> **Correction (2026-07-11, per Codex v3 critique):** the source magnitudes are *different estimands on different
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:59:> scales* (political opinion), **not** structural coefficients of the target value-of-project equation. So target
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:60:> parameters are **PROXY-INFORMED (source-informed ASSUMED)**, entering only via a declared transport-sensitivity
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:61:> set — **not** "anchored". "Anchored" is retired here; see `THREE-TIER-VARIABLE-DOMAINS.md`.
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:63:| Param | Was | Now | Source / caveat |
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:64:|---|---|---|---|
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:65:| central bias form (`a + b·true`) | ASSUMED | **PROXY-INFORMED (structural form)** | Broockman-Skovron linear-intercept-shift; form transports more safely than magnitude |
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:66:| central bias magnitude `a` | ASSUMED | **PROXY-INFORMED (source range only)** | B-S ~7–36 pts; D-L-S ~0.5/scale — **target magnitude UNIDENTIFIED**; transport-sensitivity only |
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md:67:| projection weight `w` | ASSUMED | **PROXY-INFORMED (directional; source ≈20–50% in-task)** | Gagnon-Bartsch reduced-form ~21–50%; D-L-S directional — target size UNIDENTIFIED |
