research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:1:# E4 foundation — value estimation, F vs G, and the central-arm model (literature-anchored)
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:3:> The theoretical + empirical backbone for E4 (the parity-surface rework). It replaces the retired multiplier's
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:4:> ad-hoc central-arm assumptions with an **estimation model whose form and parameter ranges are anchored to
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:5:> published evidence** on how third parties (planners) estimate others' valuations. Companion: the parameter
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:6:> harvest in `audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/E4-empirical-anchors.md`; the prior-art review that established the
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:7:> premise is `prior-art-review.md`. **Nothing here is pre-registered.**
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:9:## 1. Primitives (typed; no interpersonal cardinal-welfare claim)
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:10:Fix a project `g`, an instant, a context, a common declared response scale.
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:11:- `u_ij` — person *i*'s latent valuation of project *j* (latent random utility, McFadden 1974; latent-variable,
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:12:  Bollen 2002; scale, Stevens 1946). Its cross-person distribution is **F** with mean `μ_j`, dispersion `σ_j`.
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:13:- `S_j^A = A(u_1j,…,u_Nj)` — the project's social value under a **declared** aggregation `A` (primary: the mean;
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:14:  alternatives are separate normative estimands). No claim of interpersonally-comparable cardinal welfare.
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:15:- `M_j^C` — the **central** (planner) estimate of `S_j^A`. Distribution **G**.
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:16:- `M_j^D` — the **distributed** estimate (coverage from citizen reports).
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:18:## 2. The central's estimation model — LINEAR INTERCEPT-SHIFT + PROJECTION (the key formalization)
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:19:Anchored to the empirical form (Broockman & Skovron 2018: perceptions are *"strongly, strikingly linear"* in
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:20:reality **plus a substantial intercept shift**; Dias–Lucas–Sheffer: **directional projection** toward the
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:21:planner's own position):
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:23:```
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:24:M_j^C  =  a  +  b · S_j^A  +  w · (v_p − S̄)  +  η_j
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:25:```
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:26:- **`b` (slope, responsiveness):** the central tracks true value (b>0, near-linear). Real planners are *responsive*.
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:27:- **`a` (intercept shift, systematic bias):** a directional bias that does **not** average out (systematic, not
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:28:  random error — **not novel in itself**; false-consensus / elite–mass misperception is well established). *Source-
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:29:  domain magnitudes (political opinion, NOT project value):* B-S find overestimation of conservative support of
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:30:  **~7–36 pts** on a 0–100 scale (often >10, sometimes >20); D-L-S find **0.67** points on the ideology scale
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:31:  (point-estimate task). **Transport to project value is unverified — these size the source, not the target.**
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:32:- **`w · (v_p − S̄)` (projection):** the planner's estimate loads on **its own value `v_p` relative to the
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:33:  population mean `S̄`** — signed by where the planner sits (Gagnon-Bartsch's model: prediction of others is
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:34:  non-constant in own state iff projection `w>0`; D-L-S: planners begin from self-similar constituents). *Anchor:*
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:35:  Gagnon-Bartsch reduced-form projection is **large and directional** — over/under-prediction of others by
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:36:  **~21–50%** in-task, exceeding intrapersonal projection (~30%); it decomposes into **≈½ projection, ≈½
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:37:  task-uncertainty**.
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:38:- **`η_j` (noise):** idiosyncratic error.
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:40:**Format effect (reducible component).** D-L-S: eliciting a **distribution** instead of a point cuts the bias by
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:41:**more than half (0.67 → 0.19 points)** — planners reason about constituencies as **diverse groups, not an
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:42:average**, and point estimates **exaggerate** perceived dispersion (Dias et al. 2025). ⇒ part of `a` is a
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:43:measurement/format artifact; part is irreducible (projection + biased information). E4 should model both.
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:45:## 3. The distributed estimate `M_j^D`
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:46:Coverage-routed: aggregates actual citizen reports of `u_ij` (with adverse voice bias `β`, participation/report
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:47:noise). It reads **F** more directly than the central's proxy `M_j^C`, at the cost of `β`-bias and sampling
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:48:variance. (This is the credit-vs-coverage mechanism, now with `M_j^C` given an evidence-based form.)
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:50:## 4. Empirical anchors (parameters are PROXY-INFORMED, **not** anchored — source ≠ target)
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:51:> The literature gives **source-domain** coefficients (political opinion) on **different outcomes/scales**. They are
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:52:> **not** structural coefficients of the target value-of-project equation. Target `(a, w, b)` are therefore
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:53:> **ASSUMED, source-informed**, and enter E4 only through a declared **transport-sensitivity set** (see
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:54:> `audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design/THREE-TIER-VARIABLE-DOMAINS.md` and DESIGN_SKETCH_v4 §4), never as point anchors.
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:56:| Param | Source-domain value / range | Source |
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:57:|---|---|---|
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:58:| central form `a + b·S` | linear + systematic intercept shift | Broockman-Skovron 2018 |
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:59:| bias `a` | ~7–36 pts (0–100 scale); ~0.67 (ideology scale) | B-S 2018; Dias-Lucas-Sheffer |
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:60:| projection `w` | sizable, directional; ~21–50% in-task | Gagnon-Bartsch; D-L-S |
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:61:| format/reducible share of `a` | ~½ of the bias (0.67→0.19) | Dias-Lucas-Sheffer |
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:62:| dispersion σ (perceived vs true) | point-estimates exaggerate polarization | Dias et al. 2025 |
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:63:| citizen value distribution F | still ASSUMED (app-elicitable) | — |
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:65:## 5. The parity condition (sketch → E4's object)
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:66:Selecting on `M_j^C` vs `M_j^D`, the distributed arm delivers more true value when the central's error (bias `a` +
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:67:projection `w·(v_p−S̄)`) outweighs the distributed's degradation (voice bias `β`, sampling). The **boundary**
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:68:`{θ : m(θ) = 0}` — with `θ = (a, w, b, β, σ, …)` swept over the **declared transport-sensitivity sets** (not point
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:69:anchors) — is E4's primary object: central wins on one side, distributed on the other. Honest headline: **which side
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:70:reality falls on, and how large each region is** — not a multiplier. (The old E4-v4 harm-weight law `β = 1−η` does
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:71:**not** generalize to this form and is **retired**; the replacement is a separate joint-normal fixed-threshold
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:72:benchmark — DESIGN_SKETCH_v4 §5. The legacy nested-harm result lives only in its own legacy test.)
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:74:## 6. The meta-prediction instrument (Prelec)
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:75:The "rate + guess others" method (Prelec, Seung & McCoy 2017): each person gives a vote and a **meta-prediction**
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:76:of others' answers; the **surprisingly popular** answer (actual frequency > average predicted frequency) provably
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:77:recovers truth in the large-crowd limit. This is the established instrument for eliciting `w` and the F↔G gap; it
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:78:also formalizes *why* G systematically deviates from truth (people mis-predict the aggregate in a structured way).
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:80:## 7. Honest scope
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:81:- The magnitudes are from **political-opinion** perception; **transport to public-project value is an assumption**
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:82:  to be flagged, not asserted. What transfers with confidence is the **structural form, the mechanism, and the
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:83:  sign/plausible ranges** — not point magnitudes.
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:84:- No interpersonal cardinal welfare; aggregation declared; E4 outputs a conditional parity surface, not a
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:85:  real-world multiplier.
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:87:## Sources
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:88:- Broockman, D. & Skovron, C. (2018). "Bias in Perceptions of Public Opinion among Political Elites." *APSR* 112(3).
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:89:- Dias, N., Lucas, J. & Sheffer, L. (2026). "Beyond the mean…" *Political Science Research and Methods* (CC BY 4.0).
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:90:- Dias, N. et al. (2025). Drawing distributions reduces perceived polarization.
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:91:- Gagnon-Bartsch, T. et al. "Failures in Forecasting: An Experiment on Interpersonal Projection Bias."
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:92:- Prelec, D., Seung, H. S. & McCoy, J. (2017). "A solution to the single-question crowd wisdom problem." *Nature* 541.
research/e4-value-estimation-foundation.md:93:- Stevens (1946); Bollen (2002); McFadden (1974, 2001); Stiglitz (2017); Ross, Greene & House (1977).

